{
  "doc_id": "25794",
  "text": "Atrial fibrillation (AF) is a highly prevalent disease associated with pronounced morbidity and mortality [CITATION_1] . Accumulating evidence has demonstrated that cardiac autonomic nerve remodeling (ANR), characterized by nerve regeneration, as well as by uneven distribution of the sympathetic and vagus nerves, is involved in the pathogenesis of both acute and chronic AF [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . ANR and synergy with electricity and structural remodeling promotes one other to form a vicious cycle that induces AF [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
